{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a15e1b1c-4fa0-4f2d-b3d1-7104252b98f0","content":"CLR activation logs won't help here. They only diagnose **runtime loading/selection** issues (e.g., wrong .NET version picked, runtime fails to load). A `NullReferenceException` is an **application-level bug** — the runtime loaded fine, but your code is dereferencing a null reference.\n\nTo find the bug, you'd want to:\n\n1. **Check the stack trace** — it shows exactly which line threw the exception.\n2. **Enable first-chance exception debugging** in your IDE.\n3. **Share the stack trace** here and I can help pinpoint the cause.\n\nDo you have a stack trace, crash dump, or source code I can look at?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d126ec03-5954-4b51-b224-c78f55a6986e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there are any relevant files in the current working directory first, and also consider whether the CLR activation debugging skill would be helpful here.\n\nHowever, I should clarify something: CLR activation logs (produced by mscoree.dll) are about runtime selection and loading — they help diagnose issues like \"wrong runtime version loaded\" or \"runtime failed to load at all.\" They do NOT help diagnose NullReferenceExceptions, which are application-level bugs.\n\nLet me check if there are any files in the working directory that might give more context.","outputTokens":320,"requestId":"6805:14859A:ACE4718:BBEB1D9:69FD3DBD"},"id":"3f3ff234-aab3-4179-91ae-3a653160e67c","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:35:02.101Z","parentId":"453cf5b6-182c-4a77-b511-c3a6c32bc94d"}
